## Task 2 — Types of IDS

IDS solutions are categorized along two axes: **where they're deployed** and **how they detect threats**.

### Deployment modes

| Type | Scope | Trade-off |
|---|---|---|
| **HIDS** (Host Intrusion Detection System) | Installed on a single host; monitors only that host's activity | Deep visibility per host, but resource-intensive to manage at scale |
| **NIDS** (Network Intrusion Detection System) | Monitors traffic across the whole network | Centralized visibility, not tied to any one host |

### Detection modes

| Type | Method | Strength | Weakness |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Signature-based** | Matches traffic against a database of known attack patterns | Fast, reliable for known threats | Blind to zero-days (no existing signature) |
| **Anomaly-based** | Builds a baseline of "normal" behavior, flags deviations | Can catch zero-day/novel attacks | Prone to false positives; needs tuning |
| **Hybrid** | Combines both — signature match first, anomaly detection as a fallback | Best of both worlds | More complex to run/maintain |

**Q: Which type of IDS is deployed to detect threats throughout the network?**
**A:** Network Intrusion Detection System (NIDS)

**Q: Which IDS leverages both signature-based and anomaly-based detection techniques?**
**A:** Hybrid IDS

