## Task 3 — IDS Example: Snort

Snort (open-source, first released 1998) is the reference signature-based IDS used throughout this room. Detection logic lives in **rule files** — Snort ships with built-in rule sets covering a broad range of known attack patterns, and you can extend or override them with custom rules.

### Snort's three operating modes

| Mode | What it does | Typical use case |
|---|---|---|
| **Packet Sniffer mode** | Reads/displays traffic live with no analysis | Quick troubleshooting of network issues |
| **Packet Logger mode** | Logs all traffic (and any detections) to a PCAP file | Forensic investigation / after-the-fact root cause analysis |
| **NIDS mode** | Applies rule files against live traffic in real time, raises alerts on a match | Snort's core IDS function — proactive monitoring |

**Q: Which mode of Snort helps us log network traffic in a PCAP file?**
**A:** Packet Logging Mode

**Q: What is the primary mode of Snort called?**
**A:** Network Intrusion Detection System Mode

