## Task 4 — Snort Usage

Snort's config and rule files live in `/etc/snort` on this room's VM (note: this path is set at install time — a from-source build commonly defaults to `/usr/local/etc/snort` instead). The key file is `snort.lua`, which controls which rule files are active and defines variables such as `$HOME_NET`.

### Rule anatomy

```
alert icmp any any -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"Ping Detected"; sid:10001; rev:1;)
```

| Field | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `alert` | Action taken on match |
| `icmp` | Protocol matched |
| `any any` | Source IP / source port (any) |
| `->` | Direction of traffic |
| `$HOME_NET any` | Destination IP (network var) / destination port (any) |
| `msg` | Alert message shown on trigger |
| `sid` | Unique Signature ID for the rule |
| `rev` | Rule revision number, bumped on every edit |

### Custom rule created in this task

Added to `/etc/snort/rules/local.rules`:

```
alert icmp any any -> 127.0.0.1 any (msg:"Loopback Ping Detected"; sid:10003; rev:1;)
```

### Running Snort live (NIDS mode)

```bash
sudo snort -q -l /var/log/snort -i lo -A alert_fast -c /etc/snort/snort.lua
```

Then in a second terminal:

```bash
ping 127.0.0.1
```

Result — each ICMP echo triggered the custom rule and Snort logged a `Loopback Ping Detected` alert.

### Running Snort against a saved PCAP (offline / forensic mode)

```bash
sudo snort -q -l /var/log/snort -r Task.pcap -A alert_fast -c /etc/snort/snort.lua
```

**Q: Where is the main directory of Snort that stores its files?**
**A:** `/etc/snort`

**Q: Which field in the Snort rule indicates the revision number of the rule?**
**A:** `rev`

**Q: Which protocol is defined in the sample rule created in the task?**
**A:** `icmp`

**Q: What is the file name that contains custom rules for Snort?**
**A:** `local.rules`

