## Takeaways

- IDS ≠ IPS: detection and alerting only, no blocking.
- Signature-based detection is fast and low-noise but can't see zero-days; anomaly-based can catch novel attacks but needs tuning to keep false positives manageable — hybrid tries to get both.
- Snort's three modes map cleanly onto three real jobs: sniff (troubleshoot), log (forensics), NIDS (live detection).
- Rule structure (`action / protocol / src / direction / dst / metadata`) is worth memorizing cold — it's the same shape you'll see in every Snort rule from here on, including in the Jr Penetration Tester path.

